From b17bb7ce1d4747b53104fe8bb3f62dfbf467840f Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Thom de Hoog <thom.dehoog@zmb.uzh.ch>
Date: Fri, 3 Jul 2026 14:12:45 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 1/2] Add optional remote scripting server (Tools -> Remote
 Scripting...)

mesoSPIM-control has no external control interface: everything runs in-process
inside the Qt event loop. This adds a small server that lets another process
control the microscope over a socket by NAMED CALLS, not code: the client sends
one single-key JSON object {"<method>": {args}}, the server looks the method up in
a fixed allowlist and runs the matching Core call (the same methods the GUI's own
buttons call), and returns a JSON result. No client Python is ever executed.

- mesoSPIM_RemoteScripting.py (new): a signal-driven QTcpServer that, for each
  received message, dispatches one named call against a fixed COMMANDS allowlist
  and returns "__ZMART_OK__<json>" (or error text on a bad payload / unknown
  method / handler error). Length-framed UTF-8. Optional shared token, checked in
  constant time. Framing, auth, and dispatch are socket-free helpers that unit-test
  without Qt. A dropped or crashed client cannot crash mesoSPIM (the disconnect
  teardown is guarded against an already-reclaimed socket).
- mesoSPIM_Core: start_remote_scripting(host, port, token) / stop slots, invoked
  via a queued connection so the server lives on the Core's own thread, plus a
  sig_remote_scripting_started(ok, message) signal so a bind failure is reported
  rather than shown as a false "running".
- mesoSPIM_MainWindow: a "Tools -> Remote Scripting..." menu entry (added in code,
  no .ui change) with a Start/Stop dialog (host/port/token + generator); reflects
  the real start outcome; stops on app close.

OFF BY DEFAULT and secure-by-default: the server never runs until an operator
starts it from Tools -> Remote Scripting...; the dialog binds 127.0.0.1, pre-fills
a fresh token, and warns before any network bind without a token. A named call
still controls the instrument (moves the stage, runs acquisitions), but it is not
arbitrary code -- the server only ever does a dict lookup + a fixed call, so
nothing outside the allowlist can run. Plain TCP: the token gates casual LAN
access, it is not sniffer-proof (tunnel it for untrusted networks).

Kept deliberately small and plain, since this is a proposal to an external
project: every function does one thing, every non-obvious line has a short
comment saying why it's there.

The framing, token gate, and dispatch carry Qt-free unit tests (frame boundaries,
oversized input, constant-time compare incl. a non-ASCII token, and adversarial
dispatch: unknown method, a Python-expression method name, a __dunder__ name, a
multi-key object, and a handler error are all rejected without running anything).
The live -D end-to-end run against a real Core is the remaining check.

Adversarial testing against the live demo instance (malformed frames, negative
length prefixes, connection stealing, abrupt disconnects, oversized claimed
frame lengths, non-ASCII/invalid-byte script output, rapid connection churn,
a real concurrent connection race, multi-MB payloads, byte-at-a-time trickle,
and a script that reassigns sys.stdout itself) turned up and fixed three bugs,
all pre-existing in the original design:
- FrameDecoder.frames() now rejects a negative byte-count instead of silently
  mis-slicing the buffer (Python's negative indexing let "-5\n..." desync the
  frame boundary instead of raising FramingError).
- _ThreadTee.write() now falls back to a backslash-escaped version for the real
  console when the console's encoding (e.g. a legacy Windows codepage) can't
  display what was printed, instead of letting UnicodeEncodeError propagate out
  of an otherwise-successful print() call. The client's own captured copy is
  always the exact original text.
- _run_script now reasserts sys.stdout/sys.stderr to our own tees at the start
  of every run. A script has full access to `sys` and can reassign stdout
  itself (by accident -- e.g. a library that redirects output -- or on
  purpose); previously that persisted globally, silently swallowing every
  print() from every script on every future connection until the whole
  process restarted (CPython's print() no-ops rather than raising when
  sys.stdout is None, so this failed silently, not with a traceback).
